{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_019AFWzY4t9B6AugY4TF1j9r","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the KEY-QUESTIONS framework.\n\n**Behavior 1: History trimming to most recent 10 messages**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about a single function's logic — trimming a list to the most recent 10 messages. This is pure algorithmic logic.\n- REAL-INFRA: No OS, network, or subprocess needed.\n- MOCK-HIDE: No LLM needed to test if the trimming logic works correctly.\n- LLM-DEP: No — we're testing the trimming algorithm, not LLM output quality.\n\n\n- MULTI-STEP: No.\n\nMinimum level: **Unit**. The failure mode is in the trimming logic itself.\n\n**Behavior 2: Generated response addresses the customer's question**\n\nFor this one, mocking the LLM would hide the real issue — whether the actual model produces relevant answers. This is fundamentally an LLM-dependent behavior that needs the real model to validate properly.\n\n- MULTI-STEP: No.\n\nMinimum level: **Agentic**.\n\n**Behavior 3: Tone re-check correctly identifies too-formal response and triggers regeneration**\n\nIf the tone check uses an LLM call, then the classification quality directly matters, and mocking it would mask whether the model actually catches overly formal responses. This is LLM-dependent and requires real infrastructure to test properly.\n\nThe behavior combines both the classification accuracy and the regeneration trigger logic. Since it explicitly requires the LLM to \"correctly identify\" formal responses, that's the Agentic concern — the minimum level is **Agentic**. check is one LLM call. The behavior asks: does the tone check LLM call correctly identify formal tone AND then trigger regeneration? \n\nThe \"triggers regeneration\" could be tested at Integration (mock the tone check to return \"too formal\"), but \"correctly identifies\" requires real LLM. So **Agentic** minimum.\n\nBut actually, if we think about it as a sequence: generate response (LLM call 1) → tone check (LLM call 2 or deterministic classifier) → regenerate (LLM call 3), that's multiple agentic steps. But the behavior specifically focuses on just the tone check step and its triggering of regeneration — not necessarily requiring all steps to be real. So Agentic seems right.\n\nFor behavior 4, I need to verify the full exchange gets persisted to the database with correct timestamps. This is really about the persistence layer and the boundary between chatbot logic and the database. Using a real or local database is necessary here — mocking it would hide whether the schema and timestamps are actually stored correctly. Since we don't need real LLM output for this, **Integration** level works if we use a local in-process database.\n\nFor behavior 5, the question is whether the second response replaces the first and the customer never sees the rejected draft. This is about the orchestration layer's replacement logic. We can test this with mocked LLM responses — inject a first response and a second response, then verify only the second one gets returned to the customer. So this could be **Unit** if it's purely about the replacement logic, or **Integration** if it involves checking what gets logged versus what gets shown.\n\nThe key insight is that the LLM calls themselves can be mocked to produce deterministic outputs, so we're really testing the pipeline's state management — whether it correctly routes the second response and suppresses the first. If you only test at the unit level, you might miss bugs in how the responses are wired together across the orchestration layer. This is an **Integration** test because the failure mode lives in how the pipeline components interact, not in a single function.\n\nNow I'm assigning confidence levels to each behavior's test type, starting with the history trimming logic which is almost certainly a unit test since it's pure algorithmic work.\n\nFor the response quality check, that's heavily dependent on actual LLM performance, so agentic testing dominates at 85%. The tone re-check behavior is similarly LLM-dependent but has some integration complexity if the tone classifier is rule-based rather than model-based, so I'm splitting between agentic and integration with agentic still leading.\n\nNow looking at persistence and replacement behaviors—storing exchanges with timestamps is mostly an integration concern since it's about data handling, while the second response replacing the first involves both integration logic and some unit-level database operations. For behavior 3, I need to think through whether tone checking is a separate LLM call or a rule-based system, since that determines whether correctness depends on real model behavior or just orchestration logic.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9733,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9733},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"eda28724-c2c6-4f30-90e5-b183bb11b203","uuid":"8ab68323-6066-4a86-91d9-f13cb0b4a546"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_019AFWzY4t9B6AugY4TF1j9r","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01L3fk12Typ35MgTcPdiJfgz","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Conversation history trimmed to most recent 10 messages when full history exceeds context window","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure lives entirely in the trimming algorithm — selecting the last N messages from a list. No module boundary crossing is involved. REAL-INFRA: No OS, network, or subprocess needed. LLM-DEP: The trimming logic is deterministic; the LLM never needs to run. A unit test passing a list of 15 messages and asserting the output contains only the final 10 will catch any real failure. REJECTION-GATE for Integration: escalation would only be warranted if the trim boundary depended on a live tokenizer or a shared context-window service — the behavior description says nothing of the sort.","test_description":"Construct a mock conversation history of 15 messages, call the history-trimming function, assert the result contains exactly the 10 most recent messages in order, and assert the 5 oldest messages are absent.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.82,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Generated response addresses the customer's question rather than producing a generic or off-topic reply","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: 'Addresses the customer's question' is a quality judgment about real LLM output. A mocked LLM trivially returns whatever stub we supply, so the test always passes regardless of actual model behavior — MOCK-HIDE is fully active here. Running this 100 times with a real model could yield on-topic responses most of the time but off-topic ones occasionally, which is exactly the failure mode this behavior describes. REAL-INFRA and MULTI-STEP do not escalate beyond Agentic: this is a single generation call, no subprocess or OS dependency. REJECTION-GATE for Workflow: there is no multi-step agentic sequence; the tone re-check is a separate behavior.","test_description":"Send a concrete customer question (e.g., 'How do I reset my password?') to the real chatbot endpoint backed by the real LLM, and assert the response contains content semantically related to password reset — not a generic greeting or unrelated topic. Run with a deterministic seed or low-temperature setting if the API supports it to reduce noise.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.84,"Workflow":0.08}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Tone re-check correctly identifies when a response is too formal for a casual-tier customer and triggers regeneration","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: 'Correctly identifies' is an accuracy claim about a classification step. If the tone re-check is an LLM call (as implied by 're-prompts the LLM'), mocking it always returns the desired label and hides real misclassification — MOCK-HIDE is active. The correctness of the label depends on real model behavior, making Agentic the floor. MOCK-MISS for Integration alone: the orchestration that 'triggers regeneration' could be tested at Integration by injecting a stubbed tone classifier, but that would not catch the 'correctly identifies' part. Both failure modes are claimed in this single behavior, so the higher requirement (Agentic) governs. REJECTION-GATE for Workflow: triggering one regeneration is a single conditional branch, not a multi-step agentic sequence.","test_description":"Submit an intentionally overly formal LLM response to the real tone-checking step with a casual-tier customer context, and assert (a) the classifier labels it as too-formal, and (b) a regeneration call is issued. Use a real LLM for the tone check; stub the initial generation to supply the known-formal draft.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.73,"Workflow":0.1}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"Full exchange (user message, generated response, any regenerations) is persisted to the database with correct timestamps","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure lives at the boundary between the chatbot orchestrator and the persistence layer — schema mismatches, missing fields, wrong timestamp format. A pure unit test with a mocked DB always passes even when the actual insert call is wrong. REAL-INFRA: A local/in-process test database (e.g., SQLite or an in-memory Mongo) is sufficient to catch schema and timestamp bugs; a production external service is not required. LLM-DEP: We can inject deterministic stub responses for both the initial generation and any regenerations — the LLM never needs to be real to test persistence correctness. REJECTION-GATE for System: a local DB captures the relevant failure; no OS-level or real-network dependency is needed.","test_description":"Wire the chatbot orchestrator to a local test database with a seeded timestamp source. Inject a stub initial response and a stub regeneration, run the full exchange, then query the database and assert: the user message, both responses (draft and final), and monotonically increasing timestamps are all present with correct field names and types.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.04,"Integration":0.78,"System":0.12,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When tone check triggers regeneration, the second response replaces the first — customer never sees the rejected draft","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure is at the orchestration layer: the logic that decides which response object is forwarded to the caller versus which is suppressed. This is a multi-module interaction (tone checker result → response router → caller return value), so Unit is too low — a single function boundary will not expose misrouting. REAL-INFRA: No OS, subprocess, or real network needed; stubs for both LLM calls (returning a controllable 'formal' first response and an acceptable second) suffice. LLM-DEP: Correctness here is about routing logic, not LLM output quality — we inject both responses deterministically and assert the second is what reaches the caller. REJECTION-GATE for Agentic: mocking both LLM calls to return predefined drafts does NOT hide the failure; the failure is in the replacement logic, not in model behavior.","test_description":"With the LLM mocked to return a predefined formal draft on the first call and an acceptable draft on the second, trigger a full chatbot exchange for a casual-tier customer. Assert that the value returned to the caller is the second response, not the first, and that any API surface (return value, response DTO) contains no trace of the rejected draft.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.12,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.09,"Workflow":0.03}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9733,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9733},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"eda28724-c2c6-4f30-90e5-b183bb11b203","uuid":"551402f9-33b7-4d0e-b8ed-323b09968a50"}
